<tool name="open_dataset_evaluator_for_edit">
  <description>Open an existing dataset evaluator's edit form in the mounted playground in place. The browser stays on the current playground route and keeps the playground/dataset state intact.</description>
  <when_to_use>
    - The user wants to change an existing code or LLM evaluator's configuration (prompt, code, mapping, or output config).
    - Identify the target evaluator by name from the playground roster and pass its `datasetEvaluatorId`.
  </when_to_use>
  <user_facing_language>
    - The tool name is internal. In replies to users, call the opened surface the evaluator form.
    - Do not describe saving as approving a diff. The user saves with the form's Save action when ready.
  </user_facing_language>
  <workflow>
    - Call `open_dataset_evaluator_for_edit` first, then wait for the evaluator context and draft tools to appear.
    - After the form is mounted, call the matching `read_*_evaluator_draft`, then propose changes with `edit_*_evaluator_draft`.
    - After the user accepts a populated draft, offer to run the matching `test_*_evaluator_draft` before they save.
    - Do not promise the evaluator was updated. Persistence stays behind the user-visible Save action in the form.
  </workflow>
  <rules>
    - Only code and LLM evaluators can be opened here. If the user asks to edit a built-in evaluator, tell them built-in evaluators are not yet editable via the assistant.
    - If a code or LLM evaluator form is already open, this call is rejected. Ask the user to close the open form, then retry — do not try to discard their in-progress draft yourself.
  </rules>
</tool>
